02:49.203 --> 03:00.225
foundations around our campus certainly being a 
part of those and interacting with the students in

03:01.252 --> 03:12.347
those is a privilege and an opportunity and an 
important part of our academic life, as I see. And I

03:13.248 --> 03:17.313
haven't done more than my share, but I've enjoyed 
what I've done. And I hope to continue some of that.

03:23.842 --> 03:28.508
I think that we all need to keep our breadth Just as I 
said earlier that I go on field trips a lot. I don't

03:34.016 --> 03:40.044
know what kind of field trips people need in other 
disciplines, but in soil science you have to go

03:34.016 --> 03:40.044
into the field. And one of the things that I worked 
into to my core teaching some years ago was a

03:48.248 --> 03:57.178
half-day field trip in which I try to illustrate 
the high points of the course in terms of minerals.

03:57.198 --> 04:00.562
And that's evolved through our research. And 
every site we go to, we have some kind of a research

04:00.902 --> 04:12.775
base for 20 specimens of different conditions, 
wetlands, mine lands, soil. And I think that's

04:13.716 --> 04:15.218
important. One thing that I didn't mention, for I 
think 16 years, I was the chair of the teaching clay

04:15.653 --> 04:31.216
mineralogy

04:15.653 --> 04:31.216
symposium of the International Clay Society. It 
meets every four years. Well, that was a great

04:34.741 --> 04:37.745
opportunity. It kind of fitted in with the fact 
that I taught seminar for about that number of

04:38.146 --> 04:45.036
years in the department, graduate seminar in soil 
science. And I was privileged in that to interact

04:46.231 --> 04:59.691
with a diversity of people and ask them to 
participate as well as put something into the

04:46.231 --> 04:59.691
program myself. And I think that we need more of 
that as far out as we can reach. Sigma Xi and the

05:09.434 --> 05:20.804
people in chemistry have done the best job that I 
know about on campus by cutting across scientific

05:09.434 --> 05:20.804
barriers and bringing people together. There's a 
little chemistry in so many phases of science, and

05:21.265 --> 05:27.390
a whole lot of some. And I think that sort of thing is 
really important.

05:35.437 --> 05:38.580
And in this chromium work that I mentioned to you, I 
got down to the end of publishing that paper and got

05:39.455 --> 05:47.267
a really good set of reviews on that manuscript. 
And one of them said you should have data on the

05:47.907 --> 05:57.542
electronic status of those manganese oxides.

06:01.487 --> 06:03.951
Well, that was not something I had ever done. 
Didn't have an instrument in my department to do

06:05.033 --> 06:07.977
that. So I ferreted out a person in chemistry who 
turned out to be a well-spoken Chinaman who had

06:09.458 --> 06:26.522
finished his doctor's degree in chemistry and was 
badly needed in publication. very much agreed if

06:27.008 --> 06:32.919
he had helped me define the electronic status in 
those minerals. And within a week, we had done the

06:33.921 --> 06:37.288
most of that. And it'll appear in the journal 
within the next few months. And so that's the kind

06:41.997 --> 06:49.371
of cross-fertilization that we need a lot more of. 
And I think we'd welcome a lot of administrators

06:50.735 --> 07:05.142
back into the teaching lecture halls and back into 
the research laboratories if that could ever be

06:50.735 --> 07:05.142
managed. Anything else we've left out that we need 
to be sure to cover?

