of doing they may end up getting his doctor's 
degree in Mexico and doing his basic research at

10:44.369 --> 10:52.163
A&M, but that's all right if that's what it takes, 
as I see it. I've encountered that. I think you've

10:54.047 --> 10:55.630
done well. Should A&M attempt to get any larger?

11:02.322 --> 11:04.826
That's kind of like asking about gravity or the 
weather. I think it's really hard to give a good

11:04.907 --> 11:08.453
answer on that. I'd say that's not probably going 
to be decided by faculty like me. I would say what we

11:14.698 --> 11:21.295
need to do, we need to create cultural villages, 
scientific and cultural villages, and promote

11:22.338 --> 11:32.838
the interaction within them and among them. And 
that's the way I believe we can meet the public's

11:34.200 --> 11:39.891
need and meet our local need. We just finished. 
Last year we had a little black young lady from

11:43.341 --> 11:49.010
Corpus to come and work. She's a junior in high 
school. This is a part of their programs. They

11:53.577 --> 11:57.282
called it ALPS program, moving to higher planes. 
This year they called it high school student

11:57.302 --> 12:00.387
research. Less students. We had one from Houston 
this year. When that student came in, tall, very

12:05.217 --> 12:24.945
attractive, both McGann and other, black 
student, doesn't matter with me, very well

12:05.217 --> 12:24.945
groomed, presented herself very well, came out of 
I think one of the best high schools in Houston

12:05.217 --> 12:24.945
area, call it a century school I think. She had much 
more spirit.

12:30.854 --> 12:33.317
After she interacted with that group, I think she 
turned back into her high schoolish perspective.

12:42.477 --> 12:46.504
And as I look at it, we accomplished quite a lot. And 
so much so I'm trying to get her data book back now.

12:49.208 --> 12:54.416
She took it with her and we're exchanging letters 
and phone calls on that. But that experience in

12:56.920 --> 13:03.490
those two years has taught me that we need to we need 
to help these young people when they come in, fit

13:04.027 --> 13:12.039
into our cultural setting in a constructive way. 
And if I were doing it, if I had to have one next

13:13.000 --> 13:24.297
summer, which I have no idea whether I will or not, I 
will make it a point to spend myself or somebody in

13:13.000 --> 13:24.297
my group every lunch hour for the first week with 
that young person. Showing them different things

13:29.165 --> 13:34.570
that relate to the culture of the campus or relate 
to the science we're trying to project. And not let

13:35.291 --> 13:42.799
them get back into this very immature teenage

13:35.291 --> 13:42.799
frame. That's all I can say. All right, my next to 
last question then. Let's make believe someone

13:47.824 --> 13:50.807
hands you a check for a million dollars. with one 
condition, you must pass that check on to Texas

13:53.116 --> 14:00.067
A&M, but you decide what is to be done with that 
money. If you had the capability to make a

14:01.149 --> 14:09.762
meaningful gift to Texas A&M, for what purpose 
would you want the gift used? What's your favorite

14:09.782 --> 14:14.550
project or task or game? Well, you know, you 
really, excuse me, You really put me on the spot,

14:21.432 --> 14:30.812
because I'm obviously very selfishly oriented 
about something I know something about that I've

14:21.432 --> 14:30.812
studied about for a long time. I think if I had a 
million dollars with the freedom to use it in Texas

14:32.315 --> 14:42.276
A&M, I would try to set up a program that embraced 
the most basic parts of the science that I know

14:44.804 --> 15:01.513
something about, soils and such, and extend it to 
include the consumer.

15:03.333 --> 15:11.624
In other words, I would try to integrate basic 
research and extension as it's perceived in a

15:03.333 --> 15:11.624
classic sense. And I'd like to apply it perhaps to a 
given kind of a problem for maybe for five years.

15:20.156 --> 15:28.868
And then try to wrap it up and then perhaps move to 
another kind of a problem for the next five years.

15:29.089 --> 15:32.293
And pull in faculty into that. And that way we could 
not only be seeing what we do at the molecular level

15:32.273 --> 15:54.505
here, and a lot of our science can be done at the 
molecular level and move ahead much faster, but we

15:32.273 --> 15:54.505
need to spend part of our time out there in the 
applications area. And I think with that kind of an

15:54.525 --> 15:59.833
assemblage and an active group, I think it would 
be, we could efficiently use the resources from a

16:00.269 --> 16:05.294
million dollars. Okay, last question. After 
about a third of a century here, what feelings do

16:08.137 --> 16:13.843
you carry in your heart for Texas A&M? Well, it's a 
great place to work. It's a great place to work

16:18.408 --> 16:26.597
because it offers a lot of freedom, it offers quite 
a bit of support. It's dwindling in some respects.

16:29.927 --> 16:30.929
Not in every respect. The student money that's 
been plowed back into our department has been our

16:32.731 --> 16:39.842
salvation in recent years. I don't know if that's 
the best way to go or not, but that's the way it's

16:41.284 --> 16:44.108
going. It certainly helps.

16:50.067 --> 16:54.912
I'm just, I'm kind of tired now, and I guess I didn't 
do very well with your last question. No, no, no.

16:55.753 --> 16:57.274
Say again what your last question was. What 
feelings do you carry in your heart about Texas

16:57.294 --> 17:02.740
A&M?

17:03.561 --> 17:07.585
I'm not beyond being emotional, but I'm not very 
emotional, really. I'm more factual oriented, I

17:07.665 --> 17:10.368
think.

17:14.772 --> 17:16.294
I really like the the high purpose that A&M has 
exemplified in its selection of leaders, and the

17:18.400 --> 17:34.984
fact that I've gotten to know a significant number 
of them, but I don't go out beating the bushes to

17:18.400 --> 17:34.984
meet people very much. And I'm glad to be able to go 
anywhere else in the country and say I work for

17:36.887 --> 17:48.323
Texas A&M, and there are a lot of good people there 
doing their best. And there's a good ending right

17:49.754 --> 17:51.850
there.

